<DOC><DOCNO> AP890318-0107 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1703EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     03-18 0164</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sudan,0169</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Claim Takeover of Provincial Capital</HEAD><DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rebels from the Sudan People's LiberationArmy on Saturday claimed they had taken the southern provincialcapital of Mongalla.   The government did not confirm the reports, but Prime MinisterSadek Mahdi on Saturday met with senior military and securityofficials to review the situation in the province, Equatoria.   The rebels, in a broadcast on their clandestine Radio Liberation,said they took Mongalla from government troops on Friday. Thebroadcast, monitored in Khartoum, did not give details of thereported capture.   The southern rebels, mostly Christians and animists, oppose thegovernment, which is deominated by the north's Moslem Arab majority.They initiated the country's civil war in 1983 to push for greaterautonomy.   Mahdi has been under pressure from the military and oppositionparties to include the rebels in a broad-based government coalitionand end the civil war. Mongalla was the capital of southern Sudanunder British rule, which ended in 1956.</TEXT></DOC>